  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"total_weeks\":9,\"goal_description\":\"Late Summer Half Marathon\",\"phases\":[{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":35,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":48,\"intensity_distribution\":\"80/20 easy/hard\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"Interval\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":288,\"notes\":\"Four weeks of progressive loading. Long run extends from 12 km to roughly 18 km, adding no more than 10% per week. Tuesday carries a tempo or interval session. Saturday is the long run. The remaining days are easy or recovery. IT-band history means volume increases must be gradual and hip and glute activation work before runs is worth adding as a habit. One deload week falls at week 4, where total volume drops roughly 20% before the peak phase begins.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Peak\",\"weeks\":3,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":48,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":52,\"intensity_distribution\":\"80/20 easy/hard\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"Interval\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":284,\"notes\":\"Three weeks of peak training. Long run reaches 19 to 21 km, simulating race distance. Tuesday holds one quality session per week, alternating tempo and interval work. Paces are derived from the pace-zone index using the 10 km result of 47:30, which places easy runs at roughly 6:00/km and threshold work around 4:44/km. Total weekly volume holds steady rather than climbing, letting the body absorb accumulated fitness. Monitor any IT-band signals closely. If tightness appears, flag it before the next session rather than running through it.\",\"includes_deload\":false},{\"phase_type\":\"Taper\",\"weeks\":2,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":40,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":25,\"intensity_distribution\":\"90/10 easy/hard\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":284,\"notes\":\"Volume drops sharply over two weeks. Week 8 cuts to roughly 40 km with one short tempo effort to maintain feel. Race week reduces to around 25 km total with short, easy runs and one brief race-pace segment of 10 to 15 minutes early in the week. The long run is replaced by the race itself on August 8. Taper restlessness is normal. The feeling of losing fitness is not real at this timescale. Trust the process and keep efforts genuinely easy.\",\"includes_deload\":false}],\"rationale\":\"The runner arrives with a solid aerobic base of 35 km per week and a recent 10 km result of 47:30. Using Daniels-Gilbert zones, that performance yields a pace-zone index that supports a 1:45 half marathon target, which corresponds to roughly 4:59/km race pace. That target is achievable with consistent execution over nine weeks. The plan uses three phases. A four-week Build phase increases volume progressively and introduces structured quality work on the days already preferred, Tuesday and Saturday. A three-week Peak phase consolidates fitness at higher volume without further large increases. A two-week Taper reduces load so the runner arrives at the start line fresh. The 80/20 intensity split across Build and Peak keeps the majority of running easy, which protects the IT-band history while still driving aerobic adaptation. Hard sessions are limited to one per week to manage cumulative stress across a relatively short preparation window. Five run days are available but the plan uses four most weeks, preserving a buffer for life and for recovery. The deload in week 4 follows the standard 3-week-load, 1-week-recovery pattern and is non-negotiable given the IT-band history.\",\"warnings\":\"Nine weeks is a tight but workable window for a 1:45 half marathon goal given the current base. The plan is contingent on arriving healthy. Any IT-band tightness should be reported before it becomes pain. Do not redistribute missed mileage onto other days if a session is skipped. Simply move forward with the next scheduled run. Pace targets are derived from Daniels-Gilbert zones based on the 47:30 10 km result. If that result is more than 8 to 10 weeks old or conditions were unusual, the zones may need recalibration after the first few weeks. This plan does not constitute medical advice. Consult a physiotherapist or sports medicine professional before starting if you have any current pain or if IT-band symptoms return during training.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
